Subject: preceded_by

Subject: cellular_component
Value: A location, relative to cellular compartments and structures, occupied by a macromolecular machine when it carries out a molecular function. There are two ways in which the gene ontology describes locations of gene products: (1) relative to cellular structures (e.g., cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane) or compartments (e.g., mitochondrion), and (2) the stable macromolecular complexes of which they are parts (e.g., the ribosome).

Subject: cellular_component

Subject: oral cavity
Value: Anatomical cavity at the start of the digestive tract that that is enclosed by the mouth. The boundaries and contents vary depending on the species. In vertebrates, the boundaries are the oral opening, the cheeks, the palate and (if present) the palatoglossal arch - if this is not present then the mouth and pharynx form the oropharyngeal cavity. The buccal cavity contains the teeth, tongue and palate (when present)

Subject: mucosa
Value: A lining of mostly endodermal origin, covered in epithelium, which is involved in absorption and secretion. They line various body cavities that are exposed to the external environment and internal organs. It is at several places continuous with skin: at the nostrils, the lips, the ears, the genital area, and the anus. The sticky, thick fluid secreted by the mucous membranes and gland is termed mucus. The term mucous membrane refers to where they are found in the body and not every mucous membrane secretes mucus[WP]

Subject: epiblast (generic)
Value: In amniote animal embryology, the epiblast is a tissue type derived either from the inner cell mass in mammals or the blastodisc in birds and reptiles. It lies above the hypoblast. In mammalian embryogenesis, the columnar cells of the epiblast are adjacent to the trophoblast, while the cuboidal cells of the hypoblast are closer to the blastocoele. The epiblast, whilst referred to as the primary ectoderm, differentiates to form all three layers of the trilaminar germ disc in a process called gastrulation[WP]. The outer of the two layers of the blastoderm that form during gastrulation, corresponding to primitive ectoderm during gastrulation and to the definitive ectoderm after gastrulation[ZFA]

Subject: textual definition
Value:
2012-04-05: 
Barry Smith

The official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions'  is terrible.

Can you fix to something like:

A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.

Alan Ruttenberg

Your proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. 

On the specifics of the proposed definition:

We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. 

Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. 

We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with.  @en

Subject: independent continuant
Value: b is an independent continuant = Def. b is a continuant which is such that there is no c and no t such that b s-depends_on c at t. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [017-002])@en

Subject: process

Subject: disposition
Value: b is a disposition means: b is a realizable entity & b’s bearer is some material entity & b is such that if it ceases to exist, then its bearer is physically changed, & b’s realization occurs when and because this bearer is in some special physical circumstances, & this realization occurs in virtue of the bearer’s physical make-up. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [062-002])@en

Subject: specifically dependent continuant
Value: b is a relational specifically dependent continuant = Def. b is a specifically dependent continuant and there are n > 1 independent continuants c1, … cn which are not spatial regions are such that for all 1  i < j  n, ci  and cj share no common parts, are such that for each 1  i  n, b s-depends_on ci at every time t during the course of b’s existence (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [131-004])@en

Subject: specifically dependent continuant
Value: b is a specifically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant & there is some independent continuant c which is not a spatial region and which is such that b s-depends_on c at every time t during the course of b’s existence. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [050-003])@en

Subject: role
Value: b is a role means: b is a realizable entity & b exists because there is some single bearer that is in some special physical, social, or institutional set of circumstances in which this bearer does not have to be& b is not such that, if it ceases to exist, then the physical make-up of the bearer is thereby changed. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [061-001])@en

Subject: object aggregate

Subject: generically dependent continuant

Subject: preceded_by
Value: x is preceded by y if and only if the time point at which y ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which x starts. Formally: x preceded by y iff ω(y) <= α(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: precedes

Subject: lipid

Subject: hermaphroditic

Subject: protogynous

Subject: symbiotroph
Value: heterotroph that acquires nutrition from a symbiont

Subject: lecithotrophic larva

Subject: decomposer

Subject: promiscuity
Value: a member of one sex mates with any member of the opposite sex

Subject: apex predator

Subject: ambush predator

Subject: litter transformer

Subject: protandrous

Subject: aerobe

Subject: auxotroph

Subject: coprophage

Subject: obligate aerobe

Subject: data item

Value: x surrounded_by y iff: x is adjacent to y and for every region r adjacent to x, r overlaps y.

Value: x starts with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: α(y) = α(x) ∧ ω(y) < ω(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.

Subject: develops from part of

Subject: develops_in

Subject: has start location

Subject: has habitat

Subject: has_muscle_insertion
Value: m has_muscle_insertion s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s moves. Insertions are usually connections of muscle via tendon to bone.@en

Subject: tributary_of
Value: x tributary_of y if and only if x a channel for the flow of a substance into y, where y is larger than x. If x and y are hydrographic features, then y is the main stem of a river, or a lake or bay, but not the sea or ocean. If x and y are anatomical, then y is a vein.

Subject: spatially coextensive with
Value: x spatially_coextensive_with y if and inly if x and y have the same location

Subject: branching_part_of
Value: x is a branching part of y if and only if x is part of y and x is connected directly or indirectly to the main stem of y

Subject: has developmental potential involving
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y.

Subject: has potential to developmentally induce
Value: x has potential to developmentally induce y iff x developmentally induces y or x is capable of developmentally inducing y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y.

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y.

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q if and only if p precedes q and p and q are linked in a causal chain

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff both (a) p immediately precedes q and (b) p is causally upstream of q. In addition, the output of p  must be an input of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p 'causally upstream or within' q iff (1) the end of p is before the end of q and (2) the execution of p exerts some causal influence over the outputs of q; i.e. if p was abolished or the outputs of p were to be modified, this would necessarily affect q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: contributes to morphology of
Value: p contributes to morphology of w if and only if a change in the morphology of p entails a change in the morphology of w. Examples: every skull contributes to morphology of the head which it is a part of. Counter-example: nuclei do not generally contribute to the morphology of the cell they are part of, as they are buffered by cytoplasm.

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y if and only if more than half of the mass of x is made from y or units of the same type as y.

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y iff: more than half of the mass of x is made from parts of y

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y iff: more than half of the mass of x is made from parts of y.

Subject: has part that occurs in
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: existence starts during
Value: x existence starts during y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts and before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y).

Subject: existence starts with
Value: x starts ends with y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts with y iff α(x) = α(y).

Subject: existence overlaps
Value: x existence overlaps y if and only if either (a) the start of x is part of y or (b) the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff (α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y)) OR (ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y))

Subject: existence starts and ends during
Value: x exists during y if and only if: 1) the time point at which x begins to exist is after or equal to the time point at which y begins and 2) the time point at which x ceases to exist is before or equal to the point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y)

Subject: existence ends during
Value: x existence ends during y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends and after or equivalent to the point at which y starts. Formally: x existence ends during y iff ω(x) <= ω(y) and ω(x) >= α(y).

Subject: existence ends with
Value: x existence ends with y if and only if the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence ends with y iff ω(x) = ω(y).

Subject: transformation of
Value: x transformation of y if x is the immediate transformation of y, or is linked to y through a chain of transformation relationships

Subject: immediate transformation of
Value: x immediate transformation of y iff x immediately succeeds y temporally at a time boundary t, and all of the matter present in x at t is present in y at t, and all the matter in y at t is present in x at t

Subject: existence starts during or after
Value: x existence starts during or after y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts during or after y iff α (x) >= α (y).

Subject: existence ends during or before
Value: x existence ends during or before y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one of direct activation or direct inhibition. p may be upstream, downstream, part of or a container of q.

Subject: determined by
Value: s determined by f if and only if s is a type of system, and f is a material entity that is part of s, such that f exerts a strong causal influence on the functioning of s, and the removal of f would cause the collapse of s.

Subject: determined by part of
Value: s 'determined by part of' w if and only if there exists some f such that (1) s 'determined by' f and (2) f part_of w, or f=w.

Subject: results in ending of
Value: p results in the end of s if p results in a change of state in s whereby s either ceases to exist, or s becomes functionally impaired or s has its fate committed such that it is put on a path to be degraded.

Subject: hyperparasite of
Value: x is a hyperparasite of y iff x is a parasite of a parasite of the target organism y

Subject: lumen of
Value: x lumen_of y iff x is the space or substance that is part of y and does not cross any of the inner membranes or boundaries of y that is maximal with respect to the volume of the convex hull.

Subject: luminal space of
Value: s is luminal space of x iff s is lumen_of x and s is an immaterial entity

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: results in breakdown of
Value: p results in breakdown of c if and only if the execution of p leads to c no longer being present at the end of p

Subject: results in organization of
Value: p results in organization of c iff p results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of c

Subject: produces
Value: a produces b if some process that occurs_in a has_output b, where a and b are material entities. Examples: hybridoma cell line produces monoclonal antibody reagent; chondroblast produces avascular GAG-rich matrix.

Subject: produced_by
Value: a produced_by b iff some process that occurs_in b has_output a.

Subject: has primary input or output
Value: p 'has primary input ot output' c iff either (a) p 'has primary input' c or (b) p 'has primary output' c.

Subject: has primary output
Value: p has primary output c if (a) p has output c and (b) the goal of process is to modify, produce, or transform c.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: realized in response to
Value: r 'realized in response to' s iff, r is a realizable (e.g. a plant trait such as responsivity to drought), s is an environmental stimulus (a process), and s directly causes the realization of r.

Subject: acts on population of
Value: p acts on population of c iff c' is a collection, has members of type c, and p has participant c

Subject: different in magnitude relative to
Value: q1 different_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) NOT =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: increased in magnitude relative to
Value: q1 increased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) > magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: has cross section
Value: s3 has_cross_section s3 if and only if : there exists some 2d plane that intersects the bearer of s3, and the impression of s3 upon that plane has shape quality s2.

Subject: results in changes to anatomical or cellular structure
Value: p has anatomical participant c iff p has participant c, and c is an anatomical entity

Subject: serous membrane
Value: multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

Subject: post-embryonic stage
Value: stage succeeding embryo, including mature structure

Subject: cornea
Value: the transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

Subject: circulatory system
Value: organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc. to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis[WP].

Subject: anterior chamber of eyeball
Value: the space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, and bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and part of the crystalline lens

Subject: uvea
Value: the pigmented middle of the three concentric layers that make up an eye, consisting of the iris, ciliary body and choroid[WP,edited].

Subject: iris
Value: the adjustable membrane, composed of the stroma and pigmented epithelium, located just in front of the crystalline lens within the eye

Subject: corneal epithelium
Value: the smooth stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea

Subject: ciliary body
Value: the thickened portion of the vascular tunic, which lies between the choroid and the iris, composed of ciliary muscle and ciliary processes

Subject: optic choroid
Value: vascular layer containing connective tissue, of the eye lying between the retina and the sclera. The choroid provides oxygen and nourishment to the outer layers of the retina. Along with the ciliary body and iris, the choroid forms the uveal tract[WP].

Subject: anterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in front of, or ventral to, the lens (inclusive)

Subject: posterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in back of, or dorsal to, the lens (but not inclusive)

Subject: capsule of lens
Value: the elastic, clear, membrane-like structure, that is outer most layer of the lens

Subject: myocardium of atrium
Value: the atrial part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle

Subject: epicardium
Value: a region of the serous membrane that forms the innermost layer of the pericardium and the outer surface of the heart.

Subject: myocardium
Value: the middle layer of the heart, comprised mainly of striated cardiac muscle fibers

Subject: pericardial sac
Value: a double-walled sac containing the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Subject: gland
Value: an organ that functions as a secretory or excretory organ

Subject: cranial neural crest
Value: neural crest cells (NCCs) originating in the anterior part of the developing embryo and residing between the mid-diencephalon and the forming hindbrain; cranial NCCs migrate dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various craniofacial cartilages and bones, cranial neurons, glia, and connective tissues of the face; these cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they give rise to thymic cells, bones of the middle ear and jaw (mandible), and the odontoblasts of the tooth primordia; like their counterparts in the trunk, cranial NCCs also contribute to the developing peripheral nervous system, along with the pigmented cell (i.e. melanocyte) lineage.

Subject: smooth muscle of eye
Value: any of the striated muscles that move the eye and include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, lateral rectus, superior oblique, inferior oblique, retractor bulbi

Subject: blood vessel smooth muscle
Value: smooth muscle found within, and composing the majority of the wall of blood vessels.

Subject: respiratory system mucosa
Value: the mucous membrane lining the respiratory tract

Subject: mandibular prominence
Value: the paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip

Subject: corneo-scleral junction
Value: the edge of the cornea where it joins the sclera; the limbus is a common site for the occurrence of corneal epithelial neoplasm

Subject: pigment epithelium of eye
Value: epithelial layer of the retina, ciliary body, or iris composed of cells containing pigment granules.

Subject: prechordal mesoderm
Value: the area of axial mesoderm that develops into the prechordal plate

Subject: wall of heart
Value: wall of organ which has as its parts the endocardium, myocardium , epicardium, and the cardiac septum, surrounded by the pericardial sac proper and is continuous with the walls of the systemic and pulmonary arterial and venous trees.

Subject: anteriorly connected to
Value: x anteriorly_connected_to y iff the anterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x posterior_to y.

Subject: conduit for
Value: x is a conduit for y iff y passes through the lumen of x.

Subject: distally connected to
Value: x distally_connected_to y iff the distal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x proximal_to y.

Subject: indirectly_supplies
Value: a indirectly_supplies s iff a has a branch and the branch supplies or indirectly supplies s.

Subject: posteriorly connected to
Value: x posteriorly_connected_to y iff the posterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x anterior_to y.

Subject: proximally connected to
Value: x proximally_connected_to y iff the proximal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x distal_to y.

Subject: site_of
Value: c site_of p if c is the bearer of a disposition that is realized by a process that has p as part.
